          "body": "The psalm's middle section (vv.10-12) is among the most honest descriptions of sustained national suffering in the Psalter. The key feature is its grammar: God is the subject of every afflicting verb. 'You have tried us, O God; You have refined us as silver is refined. You brought us into the net; You laid an oppressive burden upon our loins. You made men ride over our heads; we went through fire and through water' (66:10-12). The psalmist does not name the historical event explicitly — Assyrian invasion, Babylonian exile, and the events of 701 BC under Sennacherib have all been proposed. What matters theologically is the interpretive framework: the affliction is attributed to God as divine refining, not to chance or enemy victory. The metallurgical image is precise: the smelter applies controlled, purposive heat to separate impurity from substance. Silver is not destroyed by the furnace; it is revealed as silver. The pivotal word is the 'yet' that opens v.12b — 'yet You brought us out into a place of abundance' (*revayah*, a place of spaciousness). The trial is not the final state; it is the penultimate stage before spacious relief. This framework anticipates Peter's use of the same image (1 Peter 1:6-7) and Paul's in Romans 5:3-5."
