          "title": "Personal testimony and the condition for answered prayer",
          "body": "The psalm's most intimate movement begins in v.16 with a second 'Come and...' invitation — 'Come and hear, all who fear God, and I will tell of what He has done for my soul.' Public testimony to the congregation of the fearers of God is itself a liturgical act, not merely an emotional expression. The psalmist then names the condition that made his prayer receivable: 'If I regard wickedness in my heart, the Lord will not hear' (66:18). This is a remarkable act of self-examination — before claiming that God answered, the psalmist publicly establishes that he came to God without harboring cherished sin. The term *aven* (wickedness, iniquity) refers to something actively entertained, nursed, 'regarded' in the heart. Its presence constitutes a barrier; its absence clears the channel. Calvin's comment on this verse is precise: it is not sinless perfection that is required but the absence of deliberate, self-protective unconfessed sin. The testimony that follows in v.19 is then doubly confirmed: 'But certainly God has heard; He has given heed to the voice of my prayer.' The 'certainly' (*akhen*) is emphatic — assurance, not hope."
