        "excerpt": "Shout joyfully to God, all the earth; Sing the glory of His name; Make His praise glorious.",
        "body": "The psalm opens not with a personal lament or a national complaint but with the widest possible horizon: 'all the earth.' The three imperatives of vv.1-2 — *rua* (shout joyfully), *zamar* (sing with accompaniment), *sum tehillah kavod* (make His praise glorious) — establish that what follows is not private devotion but public, cosmic, exuberant ascription. The psalmist does not ask whether the nations feel like praising; he commands it on the grounds of who God is and what He has done.\n\nThe content of the demanded praise is given in v.3: 'How awesome are Your works!' The Hebrew *yare* (awesome) carries the dual freight of terror and reverence — the God whose power compels His enemies into feigned obedience is not a domestic deity manageable by human strategies. The word *kachash* (feigned obedience, v.3) is the psalm's sharpest realism: even those who hate God must bow. It is not converted worship; it is coerced compliance that proves the point. The nations' forced submission is itself testimony to the power the psalmist wants the nations to choose to celebrate.\n\nVerse 4 anticipates eschatological fulfillment: 'All the earth will worship You, and will sing praises to You; they will sing praises to Your name.' The future tense has a prophetic edge — this is not yet universally true, but it is moving toward inevitability. The New Testament harvests this expectation explicitly in Philippians 2:10-11 ('every knee will bow... every tongue will confess') and Revelation 7:9-10 (the great multitude from every nation worshipping the Lamb). Psalm 66 is not merely Israel's hymn; it is the Psalter's contribution to what the canon calls the eschatological gathering of the nations.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rua* (shout joyfully) is a war-shout repurposed as a praise-shout — the same verb used of battle cries in Numbers 23:21. *Zamar* presupposes musical accompaniment — skill and instrument, not spontaneous feeling. *Kachash* (feigned/cringe, v.3) appears also in Psalm 18:44 and 81:15 — enemies who submit with their bodies while resisting in their hearts."
