        "excerpt": "For You have tried us, O God; You have refined us as silver is refined... yet You brought us out into a place of abundance.",
        "body": "The psalm pivots at v.8 to address the nations directly ('Bless our God, O peoples') and immediately gives them a reason: 'Who keeps us in life and does not allow our feet to slip' (66:9). The word *nephesh* (translated 'life' or 'soul') refers to the whole person — God preserves the full human being, not merely the spiritual dimension. This is the psalm's first transition from historical proof to present experience: from what God did at the Exodus to what He is currently doing in sustaining His people.\n\nThe real theological weight of this section falls in vv.10-12. The psalmist does not deny the severity of the affliction — net, oppressive burden, men riding over heads, fire, water. These are the images of military defeat, subjugation, and crushing social pressure. What is extraordinary is the attribution: every verb has God as subject. 'You have tried us... You have refined us... You brought us into the net... You laid an oppressive burden... You made men ride over our heads.' Theodicy is not evaded; it is resolved in a specific theological direction. God is not absent from the furnace; He is the smelter running it.\n\nThe metallurgical image of *tsaraph* (refining silver, v.10) is one of the Old Testament's most precise analogies for purposive suffering. The smelter applies heat sufficient to bring impurities to the surface and separate them from the pure metal — but the heat is calibrated, controlled, purposive. Silver is not destroyed by the process; it is revealed and purified. Peter uses the identical image in 1 Peter 1:6-7 ('the proof of your faith, more precious than gold which is perishable, even though tested by fire'). The canonical resonance confirms that the psalmist's framework — trial as purposive refining, not punitive destruction — is the consistent biblical theology of suffering for the people of God.\n\nThe pivotal 'yet' of v.12 is the psalm's hinge word. Everything in vv.10-12a accumulates unbearable weight; 'yet You brought us out into a place of abundance' is the reversal that makes the whole ordeal retrospectively intelligible. The Hebrew *revayah* (abundance, a place of saturation) is the opposite of every compressing image that precedes it — net, burden, oppression, fire, water. Where those images constrict, *revayah* opens. The trial was real; the deliverance is real; the God who orchestrated both is the God the nations are being asked to bless.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Bachan* (tried/tested, v.10) is the assayer's word — to examine genuineness by testing. *Tsaraph* (refined, v.10) is the metallurgist's word — smelting to purify. Both words appear together in Jeremiah 9:7 and Zechariah 13:9. *Revayah* (abundance/saturation, v.12) appears only here and in Psalm 23:5 ('my cup overflows') — spaciousness after constraint."
