        "excerpt": "Come and hear, all who fear God, and I will tell of what He has done for my soul... But certainly God has heard; He has given heed to the voice of my prayer.",
        "body": "The psalm's final movement is its most intimate and its most theologically precise. After the Selah of v.15, the communal 'we' gives way entirely to a singular 'I' — a specific individual, crisis unnamed, entering the Temple to fulfill vows spoken in desperation (v.14). The extravagance of the offering (fat beasts, rams, bulls, male goats, all as *olah*/burnt offerings in vv.13-15) signals the magnitude of the deliverance. The *olah* is total — nothing withheld, everything ascending in smoke. This is not minimal compliance; it is lavish gratitude enacted in costly worship.\n\nThe transition from vow-fulfillment (vv.13-15) to public testimony (vv.16-20) is structurally significant. The psalmist does not merely pay his vows in private and go home. He turns to the congregation of 'all who fear God' (v.16) and says: 'Come and hear what He has done for my soul.' Personal testimony is here a liturgical act — it belongs in the assembly, not merely in private reflection. The 'soul' (*nephesh*, v.16) personalizes the cosmic and national argument: the God who rules nations (v.7) and preserved a people through trial (vv.10-12) is the same God who attended to the voice of one person's prayer.\n\nVerse 18 is the psalm's most searching verse for the careful reader: 'If I regard wickedness in my heart, the Lord will not hear.' The psalmist places this condition *before* his claim that God answered — it is a pre-testimony self-examination that establishes the integrity of the testimony. The Hebrew *aven* (wickedness, iniquity) specifically refers to what is cherished and harbored, not merely committed. Calvin's comment is exact: the barrier to prayer is not moral perfection but deliberate self-deception about sin. The one who comes to God while privately nursing a known sin comes in bad faith; the channel is blocked. The psalmist's implication is that he came without that obstruction — and therefore the testimony of v.19 carries full weight: 'But certainly God has heard; He has given heed to the voice of my prayer.'\n\nThe psalm's final verse is its theological summit: 'Blessed be God, who has not turned away my prayer nor His lovingkindness from me' (66:20). The benediction (*barakh*) answers the opening command to 'bless our God' (v.8) — the circle closes. But the closing revelation is the character of God that underlies both the cosmic praise and the personal testimony: *chesed*. Covenant loyalty, steadfast love, the faithfulness that binds God to His people not because they earned it but because He pledged it. During the furnace of vv.10-12, *chesed* appeared absent; the psalmist's testimony is that it was never withdrawn. The God of the Exodus and the God of the personal prayer are the same God — and His *chesed* is the thread running through every layer of the psalm's argument.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Aven* (wickedness/iniquity, v.18) — what is cherished or nursed in the heart; cf. Psalm 36:4, Micah 2:1. *Akhen* (certainly/but certainly, v.19) — an emphatic asseveration, used to assert what the preceding conditional might have thrown into doubt. *Chesed* (lovingkindness, v.20) — covenant loyalty; the word that closes the Psalter's greatest praise-to-testimony arc."
